A primary aim of this project has been to make progress on fundamental problems in number theory, especially through the application of the geometry of Shimura varieties to automorphic forms.

The motivating problem has been to understand the arithmetic nature of the special values of L-functions of algebraic varieties and to make progress towards the Birch--Swinnerton-Dyer Conjectureand its generalizations. To this end the PI (partly in collaboration with others) has:

(a) defined a class of cycles in the Galois cohomology of the representations associated with Siegel modular eigenforms and proved that they satisfy the norm relations expected of an Euler system through a novel connection with multiplicity one results for Hecke algebras;

(b) constructed a p-adic L-function interpolating the special values of L-functions of Siegel eigenforms by a new method making use of higher coherent cohomology of Siegel modular varieties;

(c) made progress toward an `explicit reciprocity law' connecting the p-adic L-functions in (b) with the cycles in (c), yielding proofs of new cases of the Bloch--Kato Conjecture for Siegel modular forms;

(d) proved one- and two-variable Iwasawa Main Conjectures for a large class of weight two modular forms and finite slope primes p, yielding proofs of the p-part of the conjectured Birch--Swinnerton Dyer formula for the special values of the L-functions of the corresponding abelian varieties;

(e) developed a novel approach to anticyclotomic Euler systems for a large class of Galois representations, reproving and generalizing Kolyvagin's ground-breaking results for modular elliptic curves;

(f) proved the existence of non-trivial solutions to systems of diagonal equations over general p-adic field whenever the number of variables exceeds a simple bound that is quadratic in the number of equations and the degree  (the first bound that is polynomial in either). 

Additionally, this project has partially supported the research of PhD students working under the supervision of the PI. This includes:

(g) work by a PhD student on the p-adic variation of special cycles on the product of a Hilbert moduar surface and a modular curve, with applications to the Birch--Swinnerton-Dyer Conjecture for elliptic curves over quintic fields;

(h) work by a PhD student (jointly advised) on a regulator formula for p-adic L-functions of modular forms in terms of CM points that have additive or supersingular reduction at p; this makes crucial use ideas from perfectoid theory.

These results have been written up in papers that have been submitted for publication and have also been presented in invited lectures at various international conferences and workshops. 



